ckground=http://www.cafenet.plus.com/The_Magicians_Tower/Images/Background_1.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://www.cafenet.plus.com/The_Magicians_Tower/Images/Background_1.gif class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kannt00>Kannt00</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#333333>(2/19/03 7:03:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=364.topic&index=101>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: idiot socialists</span><hr size=1> People hate Bush because he's not a good diplomat.  Time and again, he makes *rhetorical* mistakes -- the information and plans he presents are generally good (sans his policy in north korea), but the way in which they're presented alienates the world.  He's just not smooth.  The whole 'axis of evil' diatribe is a prime example of one of his gaffes.<br>
<br>
About the Iraqi assassination attempt on Bush SR.. the motive for going after a country that tries to kill your leaders is not revenge -- on the contrary, it's pragmatic.  If Saddam tried to assassinate the president once, we can assume there's a decent change he'll do it again.  If he uses chemical weapons on his civilians once, we can assume it's likely he'll do it again.  If he invades his neighbours once, we can assume he will again -- and so on down the line.  <br>
<br>
We already had all the information we required to warrant a war.  The world has a short memory.  In hindsight, I wonder if going to the U.N. was a mistake.  We only went to the U.N. to placate the international community, taking the gamble that the inspectors would find the weapons we knew were there.  Now that they haven't found them, we've backed ourselves into a diplomatic corner, because we have to explain why we agreed to the inspections in the first place if we already knew we were going to invade.<br>
<br>
About Saddam keeping down Islamic fundamentalists (Islamists) -- yes, he does.  That's why Al Qaeda has traditionally spoken out against the Iraqi regime, before recently, when they did a quick turnabout to say it should be supported in the coming war against their greater enemy, America.  It also speaks to why the U.S. won't install a democratic government in Iraq when Saddam is history.  Among businessmen, academics and other secularists, there's real fear in the Arab world of Islamist takeover.  Islamists have captured the popular imagination there.  If there were a democracy in Iraq (or syria, or jordan, or saudi arabia) it's probable that Islamists would be elected.  And the first thing a real Islamist would do after getting to office would be to suspend democratic freedoms and install a repressive theocracy.  <br>
<br>
It's one of the reasons any action in the middle east is so morally yucky -- you're always dealing with the lesser of two evils.  On one hand, you want to establish the right to self-determination, but on the other you don't want to create powerful enemies.  So America, up to now, has been content to confine its goals to the support of benign dictatorships.  As a fervent fan of open societies, that irks me, but damned if I can think of a more practical alternative for the present...<br>
<br>
Kannt<br>
<br>
