<br>
This is gonna be a long one, btw...<br>
<br>
Silverblade:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>you know much about Islam? Sunni (moderate), Shiite (extremist), ok that's very simplistic but a rough idea of the two main factions.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And as far as I am aware, Baath or no Baath, his supporters are mostly Sunni muslims.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Saddam Hussein's body count, taken from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.moreorless.au.com/killers/killers.htm" target="top">this site</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Approaching two million, including between 150,000 and 340,000 Iraqis and between 450,000 and 730,000 Iranians killed during the Iran-Iraq War. Over 100,000 Kurds killed or &quot;disappeared&quot;. An estimated 1,000 Kuwaiti nationals killed following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. No reliable figures for the number of Iraqis killed during the Gulf War, with estimates varying from as few as 1,500 to as many as 200,000. No reliable figures for the number of Iraqi dissidents and Shi'ite Muslims killed during Hussein's reign. Approximately 500,000 Iraqi children dead because of international trade sanctions introduced following the Gulf War.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Gassed...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>US intelligence sources report the following use of chemical weapons by Iraq during the [Iraq-Iran] war:<br>
<br>
-Mustard gas at Haij Umran in the August 1983, killing less than 100 Iranians and Kurds.<br>
-Mustard gas at Panjwin in October-November 1983, killing 3,000 Iranians and Kurds. <br>
-Mustard gas at Majnoon Island in February-March 1984, killing about 2,500 Iranians. <br>
-Tabun nerve agent at Al Basrah in March 1984, killing about 50-100 Iranians. <br>
-Mustard gas and Tuban at Hawizah Marsh in March 1985, killing about 3,000 Iranians. <br>
-Mustard gas and Tuban at Al Faw in February 1986, killing 8,000-10,000 Iranians. <br>
-Mustard gas at Umm ar Rasas in December 1986, killing thousands of Iranians. <br>
-Mustard gas and tabun at Al Basrah in April 1987, killing about 5,000 Iranians. <br>
-Mustard gas and nerve agents at Sumar/Mehran in October 1987, killing about 3,000 Iranians. <br>
-Mustard gas and nerve agents at Halabjah on 16 March 1988, killing hundreds of Iranians and Kurd civilians. (Some estimates put the number killed at 5,000 and the number injured at 10,000.)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.unicef.org/media/publications/irqscont.pdf" target="top">UNICEF report</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (.pdf format) on child mortality in the southern regions of Iraq.  The &quot;oil for food&quot; program is controlled by Saddam Hussein in these regions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.unicef.org/media/publications/irqncont.pdf" target="top">UNICEF report</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (.pdf format) on child mortality rates in the norther region of Iraq.  The &quot;oil for food&quot; program is controlled by the UN in this region.  The difference between the two reports is stark, but not surprising.<br>
<br>
Anyway, just a couple tidbits.  Really has nothing to do with a post-Saddam Iraq, I just couldn't help but take issue with the idea that Saddam Hussein and his followers are &quot;moderates&quot;.  Yeah man...that's what I'd call moderate.<br>
<br>
/boggle<br>
<br>
Silverblade, I have looked and looked for three days for some kind of evidence...ANY kind of evidence to support what you say about out of control extremism.  I mean, I've read articles and reports by agencies and think-tanks ranging from the CIA to the Washington Institute, CNN, Reuters, British JIC, Jane's, the Washington Quarterly...hell even NPR and the BBC.  I can't even remember them all.  It has been extremely educational, and was time well spent.  But guess what...I have found exactly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nothing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that backs your claims.  Consensus?  A post-Saddam Iraq will be precarious and tricky, but not unmanageable.<br>
<br>
Well f**king duh.<br>
<br>
The current thinking is that after Saddam Hussein is removed, a US-lead coalition will  occupy and manage Iraq - not totally unlike what General MacArthur did in Japan after WWII.  Unlike in Japan, however, any temporary governance will have to be headed Iraqi civilians and backed by Western forces.  The Iraqi people would most likely not submit to having a Westerner calling the shots.  Which is fine, and completely understandable.  <br>
<br>
This occupation force will remain in place long enough to help rebuild infrastructure and build a functioning Iraqi government.  My guess is that it will be there long after that to babysit, much like we are in Bosnia/Kosovo.<br>
<br>
A few examples of this force's mandate(s) will be:<br>
To train and possibly help equip the Iraqi regular army (the RG and SRG will, by necessity, be decimated during any military action), which will play a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>major</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> role in the stabilization of a post-Saddam Iraq; to help rebuild infrastructure; to help the Iraqi army maintain security and stability; <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>to protect Iraq from any outside threat</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (e.g. Iran)<br>
<br>
I do not doubt that there will be certain ultra-extremist groups that will have a problem with any Western presence in their country.  But, well...so what?  Believe it or not, we can deal with it /GASP.  Yeah, there will be people who do not want us there.  Surprise surprise.<br>
<br>
In any case, the idea that our presence will somehow cause Iraq and the region to go completely off the deep end over night is really without base.  Actually, the reason we will <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have problems with the Shi'ites is because <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>they are Saddam Hussein's BIGGIST OPPOSITION</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for Christ's sake.  They want him gone more than we do.  Hell, I would not be surprised to see them fighting alongside us!  In fact, when speaking in terms of open, armed revolution, the Iraqi Shi'a have tried to overthrow Saddam Hussein as recently as 1991.  As did the Kurds in the north...and we know how that ended.<br>
<br>
Another misrepresentation of truth that you've put forth, which is further evidence of your overall lack of understanding, is that the Shi'a of southern Iraq will cause problems post-Saddam because Iraqi Shi'a = Iranian Shi'a.  This is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not the case</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The two groups are not the same.  <br>
<br>
During the Iran-Iraq war, the Iranians thought they could depend on the Iraqi Shi'a to flock to them and do their bidding.  This did not happen.  Why didn't it happen?  Because the two groups - although Shi'ite Muslims - are not of the same ethnicity.  The Iraqi Shi'a do not have any allegience to the Iranians.  The Iraqi Shi'a identify themselves as Arabs...and more commonly, as Iraqis.  What the Iraqi Shi'a want is proportional representation in the central government.  They make up over 60% of the population, and the ruling Ba'ath party is almost exclusively Sunni.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that is why you are wrong.  I spent a few days of casual study in my spare time and gleaned a basic understanding that I didn't have before.  I would suggest that you follow my lead before you put forth asinine arguments about something you clearly do not understand.<br>
<br>
Silverblade:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Note its Bush Jr who decides ot have war, pure revenege may have soemthing to do with it, hm? (father's assassination attempt). Or that he and his close supporters will make fortunes from oil (one way or another).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
/yawn<br>
<br>
Honestly, can't you come up with anything better than this?  Not only is it utterly void of any intellectual substance, I defy you to substantiate it.  My 12 year old cousin could do better.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, where were you people when Bill Clinton went into Haiti, Bosnia and Kosovo without the UN's permission during the 90's?  Nowhere.  Where were you in 1998 when Clinton launched cruise missiles on Iraq.  Were you even aware that he launched more cruise missiles on Iraq in '98 than were launched during the entire gulf war?  Where were you then?  Nowhere.  I find that more than a little ironic.<br>
<br>
And why were you nowhere to be found?  Because you are not really against war.  You are agianst George Bush, for whatever reason (aren't you a Brit?).  If you were really against war, as you claim, you'd have been out there protesting every time Bill Clinton used military force without the UN's permission.  And he did it a lot.<br>
<br>
Bottom line is this...<br>
<br>
When our security is threatened, we will neutralize that threat.  We will not ask YOU or anybody else for permission.  We will not sit around and wait for the debating society that is the UN to reach a decision.  Simple as that. <p><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
